column1: Summary data on annual food imports value and volume by food category and source country 1999-2017
1/ Values are obtained by HS-4 or 6 codes, by calendar year.  Includes bulk, intermediate, and consumer foods.
See Appendix for the HS-2, HS-4, and HS-6 codes corresponding to each food group.   2/ Includes prepared fish 1604 and 1605 3/ Excludes liquors.
4 / Excludes items not in total U.S. food import categories above
U.S. food import volume, by food group
1/ Import volumes are obtained by HS-4 or 6 codes, by calendar year, in product weight or processed weight.  Excludes liquid weights.
See Appendix for the HS-2, HS-4, and HS-6 codes corresponding to each food group.
2/ Number of food animals, except fowl.  3/ Includes prepared fish 1604 and 1605  4/ Excludes fruit juices.  5/ Excludes vinegar measured in kiloliters
U.S. imports of live meat animals and eggs
Excludes nonfarm animals. 1/ Sum of live bovine, swine, sheep and goats.  Excludes animals for breeding and dairy use.
2/ Includes fowl weighing less than 4.4 pounds.  3/ Includes dried eggs, egg yolks, and egg albumin.
U.S. imports of meats and products
Total red meats, fresh and frozen 1/
1/ Sum of fresh or chilled and frozen red meats and edible animal parts; excludes fowl and prepared meats.
2/ Includes salted, cured, and smoked meat, and edible animal parts; includes fowl and other meats.
U.S. imports of fish and shellfish
1/ Sum of fresh, chilled, frozen, and prepared fish, fish fillets, and shellfish.  Excludes live fish.
2/ Excludes live fish and fish fillets.
3/ Crustaceans and mollusks; excludes prepared shellfish.
4/ Includes cured and smoked fish.  Excludes fish oils and fats.
U.S. imports of vegetables and preparations
1/ Sum of fresh, frozen, dried, preserved, and prepared vegetables.  Includes seed potatoes.
2/ Includes root vegetables such as manioc (cassava), yams, taro, and arrowroot.  3/ Includes legumes and pulses.
4/ Includes preserved vegetables that are unsuitable for immediate consumption.
1/ Sum of cheese and other dairy products.  Excludes casein and milk albumin.
Import volume is based on milk weight equivalents (source: USDA Economic Research Service).
2/ Includes milk, cream, yogurt, buttermilk, whey, butter, spreads, and fats.
U.S. imports of fruit and preparations
1/ Sum of fresh or chilled, frozen, dried or preserved, and prepared fruit, and fruit juices.  Quantity excludes fruit juices.
2/ Includes bananas and plantains.  3/ Includes nut mixtures, and preserved fruits unsuitable for immediate consumption.
4/ Apple juice and orange juice rank first and second in import value and volume.  Includes tomato juice.
U.S. imports of tree and ground nuts
1/ Shelled and in shell.  Includes cashew nuts and coconuts; excludes prepared nuts.
2/ Includes desiccated coconut, seeds and peanuts in nut mixtures.  Excludes water chestnuts, palm and shea nuts, copra.
U.S. imports of coffee, tea, and spices
1/ Sum of unroasted beans, roasted and instant coffee.  Includes coffee husks and skins.
2/ Includes coffee husks and skins and coffee substitutes.
3/ Includes chicory and other substitutes for coffee.
U.S. imports of grains and grain products
1/ Sum of bulk grains, milled grain products, and cereal and bakery preparations.  Excludes grain for seed use.  Excludes potato flour and meal.
2/ Excludes corn for seed use and canary seed.  3/  Includes wheat and rice flour, and other grain products.
4/ Includes grain preparations, including pasta, baby food, baker mixes and doughs, wafers and biscuits.  Excludes tapioca.
5/ Excludes malt extracts and food preparations, which are measured in liters.
U.S. imports of vegetable oils and oilseeds
1/ Sum of crude, refined, and other vegetable oils.  Includes tropical oils.  Excludes oilseeds.
2/ Includes sesame, virgin oil, and vegetable fats
3/ Includes coconut, palm, and palm kernel oils.  4/ Uses include animal feed, flour and meal; includes copra; excludes ground nuts.
U.S. imports of sweeteners and products
1/ Sum of sugar, other sweeteners, and confections.
2/ Includes sugar cane and beets, raw and refined sugar, and molasses. 3/ Includes honey, maple syrup, molasses, and other sweeteners.
5/ Includes chewing gum.  Confections contain sugar or other sweeteners.
U.S. imports of cocoa and chocolate
1/ Sum of cocoa beans, cocoa paste, butter, and powder, and chocolate.  Includes cocoa shells and husks.
U.S. imports of sauces, essence oils, and other edibles
1/ Includes soy sauce, tomato ketchup/sauce, broths, mustard, ice cream, edible ice, protein concentrates, and vinegar.
3/ For flavoring food and drink, as well as ingredients in perfumes, cosmetics, cleaning products.
4/ Includes fish, margarine, vegetable fats.  Excludes dairy fats.  Includes inedible tallow.
5/ Includes roots, leaves, seeds, herbs, mucilage, and other plant parts used as medicaments; hop cones, saps, extracts, natural gum, and food thickeners.
Also includes yeasts, baking powder, and miscellaneous food ingredients.
1/ Sum of wine, beer, and nonalcoholic beverages.  Excludes liquors, fruit and vegetable juices.
3/ Includes vermouth and other fermented beverages.
4/ Includes waters and other imbibable liquids, unsweetened and sweetened, such as soft drinks.
5/ Liquors and ethyl alcohol are classified as non-agricultural products.  Vinegar is an agricultural product.
U.S. food import unit prices and inflation, by food group and sector
1/ Import prices are based on unit values, or import value divided by import volume.
2/ Average price per animal.  3/ Excludes juice 4/ Excludes liquors.
Appendix: HS (Harmonized System) codes for U.S. food imports

1505, 1518-1522, 2207, 2301-3215, 3302-3507 (except egg albumin in 3502) and higher codes.
Excludes vitamins and pharmaceuticals, but includes natural medicaments for ingestion (HS 121190).
U.S. food imports, estimated value by country
1/ Values are estimated based on country shares of total U.S. import value for foods (HS 01-04, 07-13, 15-22, 33)
and calibrated with respect to total U.S. food imports as estimated in worksheet "FOOD$".
